# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1902-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The 1902 Baltimore Orioles season finished with the Orioles in 8th place in the American League (AL) with a record of 50–88.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The team was managed by John McGraw and Wilbert Robinson.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The team played at Oriole Park in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] During the season, Andrew Freedman, principal owner of the National League's (NL) New York Giants, with the financial backing of John T.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush, principal owner of the NL's Cincinnati Reds, purchased the Orioles from John Mahon, who was deeply in debt.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] They raided the Orioles roster, releasing several of Baltimore's better players so that they could sign them to the Giants and Reds.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] AL president Ban Johnson seized control of the Orioles the next day and restocked their roster with players received on loan from other AL teams.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles' second season in Baltimore would ultimately prove to be their last, as after the season the team was replaced by the New York Highlanders, now known as the New York Yankees.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Knowing that placing a franchise in New York City was key to the success of the American League (AL), AL president Ban Johnson secretly met with principal owner John Mahon and player-manager John McGraw, who was also a part-owner, before the season about relocating to New York.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] However, the transfer did not occur when they could not find a suitable venue for the team.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In March, Mike Donlin went on a drinking binge in Baltimore, during which he was arrested for urinating in public and assaulting two chorus girls.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles released Donlin when he was sentenced to six months in prison.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Notable players jumped to the Orioles from the rival National League (NL).
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In December 1901, Joe Kelley jumped from the Brooklyn Superbas.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Later in the offseason, Jimmy Sheckard also jumped from Brooklyn.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kip Selbach and Jim Jackson jumped from the New York Giants, Ernie Courtney jumped from the Boston Beaneaters, Tom Hughes jumped from the Chicago Orphans, and Dan McGann jumped from the St.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles signed Bill Keister as a free agent.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] With these transactions, the Orioles were seen as a contender in the AL pennant going into the 1902 season.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles drew over 10,000 fans on Opening Day.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Three players returned to the NL in April 1902.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Jack Dunn and Steve Brodie jumped to the Giants in April.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Sheckard changed his mind about playing for the Orioles after four games, returning to Brooklyn.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Many Orioles found themselves suspended by Johnson by midseason, including McGraw and Kelley.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In early July, McGraw resigned from the team and signed with the New York Giants of the NL.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] At this point, the Orioles had a 26–31 record.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kelley and Wilbert Robinson succeeded McGraw as player-managers.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The franchise began to fall into significant debt by July.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kelley, son-in-law of part-owner John Mahon, reported that the team owed as much as $12,000 ($446,538 in current dollar terms).
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Unable to afford that debt, Mahon purchased shares of the team from Kelley and McGraw.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] With this, Mahon became the majority shareholder, owning 201 of the team's 400 shares.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] On July 17, 1902, Mahon sold his interest in the Orioles to Andrew Freedman, principal owner of the Giants, and John T.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush, principal owner of the Cincinnati Reds, also of the NL.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The transaction was reported to have been in the range of $20,000 ($744,231 in current dollar terms).
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] That day, Freedman and Brush released Kelley, Joe McGinnity, Roger Bresnahan, Jack Cronin, Cy Seymour, and Dan McGann from their Oriole contracts.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush then signed Kelley and Seymour to the Reds, while Freedman signed McGinnity, Bresnahan, Cronin, and McGann, joining McGraw, his new player-manager, on the Giants.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Though Kip Selbach and Jimmy Williams were both pressed to agree to relocate as well, they refused to leave Baltimore, saying they would honor their two-year contracts.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] McGinnity allegedly attempted to contact Johnson that night, offering to stay with the Orioles if he could receive Johnson's personal assurance that he was welcome to stay.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] McGinnity did not hear back from Johnson, who had left his phone off the hook that night to avoid being contacted, and joined his teammates with the Giants.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] On that day, the Orioles were forced to forfeit their game against the St.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Louis Browns, as Baltimore lacked the minimum number of players required to compete.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Johnson used a league rule to join the Orioles' minority owners to seize control of the team.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Now running the Orioles, Johnson sought to restock the team.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] He requested players from the other AL franchises to fill the Orioles' roster.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Sport McAllister was loaned to the Orioles from the Detroit Tigers for three games, but the Tigers requested McAllister back, as the Orioles came to Detroit to play the Tigers.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles received Pop Dillon from the Tigers, but released him after using him in two games.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Snake Wiltse was sent to the Orioles from the Philadelphia Athletics on July 19, but he struggled for the Orioles.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles also received Lew Drill on loan from the Washington Senators, sold Charlie Shields to the St.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Louis Browns and purchased Jack Thoney from the Cleveland Bronchos.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles finished the season with a 50–88 record, good for last place in the AL.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] For their final game at Oriole Park, the team drew only 138 fans.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] During the owners meetings in late 1902, the franchise was transferred to New York.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] MLB would not return to Baltimore until the former Browns moved to Baltimore in 1954.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The **1902 Boston Americans season** was the second season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished third in the American League (AL) with a record of 77 wins and 60 losses, 6+1⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans bolstered their pitching by recruiting Bill Dinneen, who jumped from the Boston Beaneaters.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Dinneen and Cy Young would become the "one-two" pitching combination for the Boston Americans.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Augusta, Georgia.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 11 home runs and had 121 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .342 batting average.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 45 appearances (43 starts) and pitched 41 complete games with a 32–11 record and 2.15 ERA, while striking out 160 in 384+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The team had one game end in a tie; August 18 vs.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1902 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 32nd season of the franchise.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1902 Brooklyn Superbas** finished in a distant second place in the National League, 27.5 games behind the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1902-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
